m2Eclipse is an Eclipse plug-in that provides Maven integration for Eclipse. http://eclipse.org/m2e/
Subversive is an Eclipse plug-in that provides SVN integration for Eclipse. http://www.eclipse.org/subversive/

Eclipse is an open source community providing a leading development platform for Java and other languages built on an extensible framework. The Eclipse web site at http://www.eclipse.org/ gives access to the Eclipse tools and the wide range of official Eclipse projects that extend the basic platform.

Eclipse plug-ins are extensions to the Eclipse platform that implement one or more extension points defined by the platform or other plug-ins. Most of the functionality Eclipse framework itself is built as plug-ins.

Sonar is an open source tool for quality management that allow you to run a set of tests on your software. The Sonar plug-in gives an Eclipse perspective in which the information is provided. http://www.sonarsource.org/

The uCC should plug-in based. This means that new components for configuring the AAL-Space provided by uAAL can be included easily. Installation and Configuration of application are also plug-in's but fixed included within the tool.
Currently we have in mind to use a web-based approach, to be platform independent. But in general the View should be independent from the Core.
The core of the uCC should provide the basic functionality on command line level. This means in the beginning mainly to download, install and configure applications from the uStore.

Because we are need to connect to the uStore to get information about apps and download them, we also need a class that is responsible for managing all this.

Our current idea is an extension of the OSGi command line, that allows the basic functions we will provide in Task 3.5 (like install apps and so on). This allows us an easy and view independent access to them.

The uCCCore is the connection to the OSGi Framework and therefore need to have an Activator. Other part of the uCC (View and Plug-Ins) not necessary need to be valid bundles and maybe can get there information from the core (if needed).

Maybe "DependencyChecker" is not the best name, because most checking will be done by conformance tools and uStore. But we also need to check locally if middleware is installed/running correctly all needed bundles included to give appropriate feedback to the user.

The uCC should plug-in based. This means that new components for configuring the AAL-Space provided by uAAL can be included easily. Installation and Configuration of application are also plug-in's but fixed included within the tool.

We need a component that is able to read-out the files created by Tom's tool. The questions is how and where to generate the generic views for different system (Windows, Android, ...). Can we already solve this within the plug-in, must solve this in the View or make a mixture (core simplifies the creation).

Like given by the name of this plug-in it will be responsible to install applications downloaded from the uStore in the local environment. Therefore it will take use of the DependencyChecker and the uStoreConnector. Install primary could mean to copy one or many bundles into the auto-start folder of the OSGi runtime and check if they are well started...

A plug-in need to be a part of the core and may have also own graphical interfaces that should be shown in the main view. This class should provide the interface to realize this.
The MainView is the central window from the uCC. It provides a frame for all subwindows given by the plug-ins, shows menus, status bar, ...
